olière, and Shakespeare. The direct, humorous, and provocative style of this work, which tackles the subject of humour with a vast array of vivid examples encountered on every page, will certainly appeal to the contemporary reader. Vladimir Propp takes various forms of laughter in literature and real life and addresses questions such as the comic of similarity, the comic of difference, parody, duping, incongruity, lying, ritual laughter, and carnival laughter. The author of the widely acclaimed Morphology of the Folktale has written an original, comprehensive, and exciting study on how humour works, and on everything you wanted to know about the genre, in a clear, approachable, and insightful manner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aComic, The, in literature. 0aHumor in literature. 0aLaughter in literature. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aDebbèche, Jean-Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerron, Paul J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269781240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442697812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442697812.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK